S<sw-ex>i</sw-ex><sl>r</sl> London 4<sw-sup>th</sw-sup> May 1693
Yesterday being the last of <brev-y>th</brev-y><sl>e</sl> Term
Diuers persons were discharged among them
The Lord Sturton butt one Johnson Who
came from ffrance was Continued vpon his recognizance
recognizance
Yesterday Captain Wilkshire Comission<sw-ex>er</sw-ex>
and Mr Cooper Storekeeper of <brev-y>th</brev-y><sl>e</sl> Dock yard
att Portsmouth were to have bin tryed vpon
a 2<sw-sup>d</sw-sup> informac<sw-ex>i</sw-ex>on butt the Atturny Generall
entered a Noli prosequi thereon to discharg
their proceedings last night an express was
dispatched to the 3 admiralls from Secretary
Trenchards office Tis Suppossed to saile
The Earl of Nottingham received yesterday
Letters <brev-y>th</brev-y><sw-ex>a</sw-ex><sl>t</sl> his Majestys Shipp the Mountague

An Express arrived from Scotland on
Sunday w<sw-ex>i</sw-ex><sl>th</sl> an account that there Was
now discovered the Debth of <brev-y>th</brev-y><sl>e</sl> late plott
of all <brev-y>th</brev-y><sl>e</sl> letters writt by K<sw-ex>ing</sw-ex> James to his

and there is great search made after <brev-y>th</brev-y><sw-ex>e</sw-ex><sl>m</sl>
On Sunday wee received a fforraign
Mayle and yesterdays Gazett hauing
